WEBVTT

00:03.870 --> 00:06.566
- Previously on
"New Amsterdam"...

00:06.610 --> 00:08.305
- His name was Muhammad.
He asked me to marry him.

00:08.350 --> 00:10.784
- Broke up?
- Brain aneurysm.

00:10.830 --> 00:12.218
I still miss him.

00:12.270 --> 00:13.487
- I told you about the songs
I'm writing,

00:13.530 --> 00:14.610
well, I'd love to make a demo.

00:14.660 --> 00:16.093
I was wondering if you could...

00:16.140 --> 00:17.311
- Give you money?

00:17.360 --> 00:19.271
Don't think it's a good idea.

00:19.320 --> 00:22.096
- I have plans with Ella.

00:22.150 --> 00:25.051
- Ella?
- Thanks for introducing us.

00:25.110 --> 00:28.671
- I've been taking a little bit
more Adderall than prescribed.

00:28.720 --> 00:33.066
- I think that I need to report
an impaired physician.

01:11.590 --> 01:13.364
- Don't forget to go over
the rib.

01:13.420 --> 01:16.150
The vein, the artery,
and the nerve run under, okay?

01:18.810 --> 01:20.459
What you got?

01:20.510 --> 01:22.558
- EMS notification,
diabetic coma on the way.

01:22.600 --> 01:24.204
- Ooh, sounds interesting.

01:24.250 --> 01:25.808
- I thought you had
a VIP patient?

01:25.860 --> 01:28.203
- Ah, that's after my shift.
I've got time to take one more.

01:28.260 --> 01:31.161
- Of course you do.

01:31.220 --> 01:34.383
- Allison Medrano, 68-year-old
fishing boat captain

01:34.440 --> 01:35.737
with Type II diabetes.

01:35.790 --> 01:37.132
Rescued by Coast Guard,
unconscious.

01:37.180 --> 01:38.829
Finger stick blood sugar, 745.

01:38.880 --> 01:41.132
She's received ten units
sub q times four,

01:41.180 --> 01:42.351
but she's still unresponsive.

01:42.400 --> 01:44.391
Found these in her pocket.

01:44.450 --> 01:48.409
- Diabetes meds prescribed by
a Dr. Jessica Medrano.

01:48.450 --> 01:50.702
- She's a primary care doctor
here.

01:50.760 --> 01:52.182
This could be her mom.

01:52.240 --> 01:53.628
Let's page Max and Dr. Medrano,

01:53.670 --> 01:55.888
and let's get her into
Trauma One.

02:14.300 --> 02:15.824
What are you doing?

02:17.700 --> 02:20.863
- Do you see that man?

02:20.920 --> 02:23.559
He's my son.

02:23.620 --> 02:26.134
- And you hiding all the way
over here because...

02:26.180 --> 02:27.704
- If you believe two people
are together

02:27.750 --> 02:29.798
for the wrong reason,
it's your responsibility to--

02:29.840 --> 02:31.751
- Oh, no, no.
See--no, no, nope, nope.

02:31.800 --> 02:33.279
I'm gonna stop you right there.

02:33.320 --> 02:35.185
See, as a rule,
I don't do family drama.

02:35.240 --> 02:37.231
So, if you wanna talk
about that,

02:37.280 --> 02:38.804
I recommend you talk to Iggy.

02:38.850 --> 02:41.455
- Iggy is busy all day,
and there is no family drama.

02:41.500 --> 02:42.808
- Then why are you hiding?

02:42.850 --> 02:45.728
- Because I need to see if
my son lS--

02:45.770 --> 02:47.852
- No, no.
No family drama, man.

02:47.900 --> 02:50.209
Look, my only advice for you:

02:50.250 --> 02:51.808
stay out of your boy's
dating life.

02:54.780 --> 02:56.816
Hey, you want a coffee, Vijay?
- Ooh.

02:59.520 --> 03:01.738
- Blood PH of 7.19.

03:01.790 --> 03:03.269
- Blood sugar still over 700.

03:03.310 --> 03:04.914
Injecting ten more units of
insulin.

03:06.700 --> 03:08.565
- Mom.
- Hey.

03:08.620 --> 03:09.746
- Can I get some water?

03:09.790 --> 03:11.929
- Absolutely.
Uh, Casey?

03:11.970 --> 03:13.528
- On it.

03:13.580 --> 03:16.219
- Ms. Medrano, you're at
New Amsterdam Hospital,

03:16.280 --> 03:18.714
and I will be happy to answer
any questions you might have.

03:18.760 --> 03:20.887
- Where's my boat?

03:20.930 --> 03:22.488
- Except for that one.

03:22.550 --> 03:23.801
I--I don't know what
that means.

03:23.850 --> 03:25.283
- She's captain of
a fishing boat.

03:25.330 --> 03:26.809
- Seriously?

03:26.850 --> 03:29.466
- What, you expecting
a peg leg and a parrot?

03:29.510 --> 03:32.331
- No, but, uh, that'd be cool.

03:32.380 --> 03:34.371
I just didn't realize there
were any of you left

03:34.430 --> 03:35.852
in New York City.

03:35.910 --> 03:38.424
- There's not.
Industry moved on; she didn't.

03:38.470 --> 03:39.869
- Huh.

03:39.910 --> 03:41.775
Fishing boat captain in
New York City,

03:41.830 --> 03:44.515
that--that's a throwback.

03:44.570 --> 03:47.209
What an interesting job.
- Mm-hmm.

03:49.270 --> 03:50.350
- Excuse me.

03:53.010 --> 03:54.739
- He does that sometimes.

03:56.750 --> 04:00.368
- Nourishment Consultant,
Media Distribution Ofﬁcer,

04:00.410 --> 04:01.627
pneumatic tube repair?

04:01.670 --> 04:02.796
What do these people
even do?

04:02.850 --> 04:04.363
- Aren't you
the Medical Director?

04:04.410 --> 04:05.365
Aren't you supposed to know?

04:05.410 --> 04:07.321
Oh.

04:07.370 --> 04:08.621
Hello.

04:10.460 --> 04:12.280
- Has anyone here ever met
a Chiropodist?

04:12.330 --> 04:13.809
Of course you haven't,
because they don't exist.

04:13.860 --> 04:16.283
But 100 years ago,
there was a whole department

04:16.340 --> 04:18.467
full of 'em cutting
people's toenails.

04:18.510 --> 04:20.649
But the field evolved
and Chiropody was

04:20.690 --> 04:22.032
absorbed into Podiatry.

04:22.080 --> 04:24.298
Chiropodists became obsolete.

04:24.350 --> 04:26.295
Why are we talking about
Chiropodists?

04:26.350 --> 04:27.476
- Because you're firing us?

04:27.520 --> 04:29.249
- No.

04:29.310 --> 04:31.653
We're talking about
Chiropodists not just because

04:31.700 --> 04:34.692
it's a really fun word to say,
but because I'm willing to bet

04:34.750 --> 04:36.354
that right here,
at New Amsterdam,

04:36.400 --> 04:37.389
there are people here
whose jobs

04:37.450 --> 04:39.395
are obsolete, bogus, wasted.

04:39.450 --> 04:41.406
Jobs that aren't really jobs
at all.

04:41.450 --> 04:43.577
But just because your job
is obsolete,

04:43.630 --> 04:45.530
doesn't mean you are.

04:45.580 --> 04:47.491
- Wait, are you firing us?
- No.

04:47.540 --> 04:50.282
I wanna find people whose
talents are being wasted

04:50.330 --> 04:51.581
and give them meaningful work.

04:51.630 --> 04:53.586
I wanna give them jobs
that matter.

04:53.640 --> 04:56.370
Every time a patient
walks out our doors,

04:56.420 --> 04:58.672
our people should feel like
they contributed to

04:58.730 --> 04:59.890
that patient's success.

04:59.950 --> 05:01.633
And no...

05:01.690 --> 05:03.419
I am not firing anybody.

05:03.470 --> 05:05.688
Every department is gonna
try this experiment,

05:05.740 --> 05:07.776
just for one day, stop working.

05:07.820 --> 05:10.903
Just sit there, stand there,
don't do anything.

05:10.960 --> 05:12.689
And if nobody misses
what you do

05:12.740 --> 05:15.391
or needs you to do something
for one whole day,

05:15.440 --> 05:17.351
then your job may be obsolete.

05:17.400 --> 05:19.482
Clearly not talking about
those people.

05:19.530 --> 05:23.614
But if it is you, come to me.
I wanna find you a new job.

05:23.670 --> 05:26.969
A job that inspires you,
a job that makes a difference,

05:27.020 --> 05:30.456
a job that makes you
an integral part of

05:30.500 --> 05:32.491
New Amsterdam's mission.

05:38.510 --> 05:40.466
- Dr. Panthaki?

05:40.510 --> 05:42.899
- Dr. Sharpe.

05:42.950 --> 05:44.463
- Fancy meeting you here.

05:44.510 --> 05:46.819
- Yeah, well, no.

05:46.860 --> 05:47.986
- No?

05:48.040 --> 05:49.644
- I came here to see a patient,

05:49.690 --> 05:51.078
and I thought I'd stop by
and say hi.

05:51.130 --> 05:52.904
I walked by your office,

05:52.960 --> 05:54.996
but they said you were on
the floor, so here I am,

05:55.050 --> 05:58.395
casually bumping into you,
accidentally on purpose.

05:58.440 --> 05:59.873
- I see.

05:59.920 --> 06:02.480
- I can also accidentally
on purpose leave.

06:02.530 --> 06:06.136
- No, I'm glad that you decided
to stop by...

06:07.410 --> 06:08.889
Accidentally on purpose.

06:09.890 --> 06:13.405
- And would you consider
joining me on an adventure?

06:13.460 --> 06:14.848
- An adventure?

06:14.890 --> 06:15.970
- It's a small adventure.

06:16.020 --> 06:17.544
Do you like Radiohead?

06:17.590 --> 06:18.841
- Yes.

06:18.900 --> 06:20.674
Love them.

06:20.720 --> 06:22.984
- Then we'll need to be on
a train from Penn Station

06:23.030 --> 06:24.372
in a few hours.

06:24.420 --> 06:26.376
- Why?
Where are we going?

06:26.420 --> 06:28.024
- Philadelphia.

06:28.080 --> 06:30.036
- So we'd be staying overnight?

06:31.730 --> 06:34.039
- We would be.

06:34.080 --> 06:35.638
- You know, yeah, no,

06:35.690 --> 06:38.864
I can't do that
right now...with you.

06:38.920 --> 06:40.603
- Okay.

06:40.660 --> 06:43.823
- I mean, I want to eventually,
I'm just...

06:43.880 --> 06:46.576
- Helen, I'll make you
a bootleg.

06:53.500 --> 06:56.492
- Well, I'm still not 100% sure
as to why Ms. Medrano

06:56.540 --> 06:58.144
collapsed on the ship.

06:58.200 --> 07:00.543
- Did her blood sugar spike
before or after the fall?

07:00.590 --> 07:01.932
- That's the million dollar
question.

07:01.980 --> 07:04.448
So, this must be some VIP
for you to drag me

07:04.510 --> 07:05.989
all the way up here.

07:06.030 --> 07:07.725
- It is.

07:07.770 --> 07:10.819
- So, who's the patient?

07:12.860 --> 07:14.077
- You are.

07:21.390 --> 07:23.176
- Yeah--hey, uh, Dora...

07:26.440 --> 07:28.351
- Hold on.

07:28.400 --> 07:32.131
Ijust wanna take in this
momentous occasion.

07:32.190 --> 07:33.225
- What occasion?

07:33.270 --> 07:34.794
- The day you chased after me.

07:34.840 --> 07:37.308
I wanna remember everything:
what I was wearing,

07:37.360 --> 07:38.497
where I was standing...

07:38.540 --> 07:39.973
- You haven't texted me.

07:40.020 --> 07:40.975
- Nope.
- Or paged me.

07:41.020 --> 07:42.453
- Did you miss me?

07:42.500 --> 07:44.058
- Well, I just figured by now
people would--

07:44.110 --> 07:45.281
- People would admit that
they were getting paid

07:45.330 --> 07:46.285
to not work?

07:46.330 --> 07:47.501
- That's not exactly--

07:47.550 --> 07:49.063
- And that they would ask you
for work,

07:49.120 --> 07:50.894
when they could just keep on
doing nothing?

07:50.940 --> 07:52.248
- That's not really in
the spirit of what I'm trying--

07:52.290 --> 07:54.338
- If it was me,
no way I'd tell you.

07:54.380 --> 07:55.938
- Max...

07:57.170 --> 07:59.468
What's going on with, um,
you know?

08:01.210 --> 08:02.472
- She's with Iggy.

08:06.480 --> 08:07.913
- I think I'm gonna be sick.

08:07.960 --> 08:10.178
- You did the right thing.

08:10.220 --> 08:11.391
- As a doctor, sure.

08:11.440 --> 08:13.522
But as a friend,
I absolutely did not.

08:13.580 --> 08:18.404
- You absolutely did,
as a doctor and as a friend.

08:28.370 --> 08:30.099
All right.

08:30.160 --> 08:31.889
Feel free to sit.

08:31.940 --> 08:33.498
- I'm fine.

08:34.600 --> 08:36.204
- Okay.

08:39.430 --> 08:40.909
All right.

08:40.950 --> 08:44.556
So, it says here you went to
Whitman College.

08:44.610 --> 08:46.510
- Yep.

08:46.560 --> 08:50.041
- All the way up in
Walla Walla, Washington, huh?

08:50.090 --> 08:51.569
Did you like it?

08:51.610 --> 08:53.566
- Loved it.

08:53.620 --> 08:56.134
- Why there?

08:56.180 --> 08:58.569
- Well, I guess it's because
I thought that they would

08:58.620 --> 09:01.350
prepare me for a career in
lifesaving medicine.

09:01.410 --> 09:03.401
One which I would love to
get back to right now,

09:03.450 --> 09:06.442
unless you're gonna tell me
what this all about.

09:06.500 --> 09:08.229
- Okay.

09:08.280 --> 09:11.454
Somebody reported that you have
a problem with Adderall.

09:13.070 --> 09:15.026
Sharpe.

09:15.070 --> 09:17.118
- I'm not at liberty to discuss
that with you.

09:17.160 --> 09:19.151
- Please.

09:19.210 --> 09:21.337
So, do you?

09:21.380 --> 09:22.984
- Do I what?

09:23.040 --> 09:24.598
- Do you have a problem
with Adderall?

09:24.650 --> 09:28.427
- No.
- Okay.

09:28.480 --> 09:30.038
Do you have any idea why
someone would suggest

09:30.090 --> 09:31.899
that you do?

09:31.960 --> 09:34.349
- Look, I spoke to Sharpe about
a personal matter,

09:34.390 --> 09:36.005
a minor personal matter,

09:36.050 --> 09:38.917
and she has blown it way out of
proportion.

09:38.960 --> 09:42.578
- Right, well, can you tell me
about the personal matter?

09:42.620 --> 09:44.224
- No.

09:45.710 --> 09:47.098
- Why not?

09:47.150 --> 09:48.663
- Because it's personal.

09:48.710 --> 09:51.144
And because quite frankly,
this whole ambush

09:51.190 --> 09:52.589
is unbelievably insulting,

09:52.630 --> 09:54.359
and I'm done pretending like
it isn't.

09:54.410 --> 09:55.968
- I wouldn't do that.

10:02.290 --> 10:04.281
I have been empowered by
the hospital to determine

10:04.340 --> 10:06.501
if you've been operating
as an impaired physician.

10:10.080 --> 10:11.388
- And if you have a problem
with Adderall,

10:11.430 --> 10:12.988
I will tell Max
and he'll report it

10:13.040 --> 10:15.213
to the medical board.

10:15.260 --> 10:19.173
- So, what, if I leave,
I'm suspended?

10:19.220 --> 10:22.439
- No, if you leave,
you're fired.

10:27.670 --> 10:29.228
- Dr. Reynolds.
- Dr. Goodwin.

10:29.280 --> 10:31.350
- I need a consult.
- What's the case?

10:31.410 --> 10:32.570
- Allison Medrano,
let's just call her

10:32.630 --> 10:33.972
a "non-compliant diabetic."

10:34.020 --> 10:35.533
- Hemoglobin A1C off the chart?

10:35.590 --> 10:37.069
- Yeah, and I wanna make sure
her collapse wasn't due to

10:37.110 --> 10:38.452
a silent heart attack.

10:38.500 --> 10:39.626
- Okay, I'll stop by after
the rounds.

10:41.160 --> 10:42.502
heard about _
your speech this mornIng.

10:42.550 --> 10:44.154
- You got someone for me
in your department?

10:44.200 --> 10:45.679
- No, everyone in
my department's on overdrive.

10:45.730 --> 10:47.152
But did you know there's a guy
in the basement

10:47.210 --> 10:49.166
who still prints X-rays?
-%mwm

10:49.210 --> 10:50.689
went digital a decade ago.

10:50.730 --> 10:53.290
- Well, that's why you should
check on him.

11:00.570 --> 11:01.525
Hello?

11:01.570 --> 11:03.470
- Need an X-ray?

11:03.530 --> 11:05.088
- Does that thing still work?

11:05.140 --> 11:07.700
- What, the XR-180?
Oh, yeah.

11:07.750 --> 11:10.218
And I like to keep it
nice and shiny, just in case.

11:11.490 --> 11:12.707
- When was the last time
someone ordered

11:12.750 --> 11:15.401
an old-fashioned X-ray
from you?

11:15.450 --> 11:19.409
- Uh, 2008...give or take.

11:19.460 --> 11:24.068
- So, you just been
down here since 2008?

11:25.720 --> 11:28.541
Doing what?

11:28.600 --> 11:31.410
- Am I about to get fired?
- Do you like your job?

11:34.380 --> 11:37.383
I loved it, actually.
Everybody needed me.

11:37.430 --> 11:39.250
Docs used to say nobody handled

11:39.300 --> 11:41.518
radiograph paper better than
I did.

11:41.570 --> 11:43.515
- I'm Max Goodwin,
I'm the Medical Director here.

11:43.570 --> 11:46.562
- Aw, nuts.
I am gonna get fired.

11:46.610 --> 11:49.693
- No, no, I'd liked to
find you a new job.

11:49.750 --> 11:53.265
A job that makes you feel
needed again.

11:53.320 --> 11:54.742
Would you be interested?

11:54.800 --> 11:57.610
- It's like you can see
right through me.

11:59.800 --> 12:01.620
It's an X-ray joke.
- X-ray joke.

12:01.670 --> 12:03.809
It's great.
So what do you say?

12:03.850 --> 12:06.842
- You know, with technology
being what it is

12:06.900 --> 12:09.198
and me being as old as I am,

12:09.250 --> 12:13.596
I think I'm just gonna
ride it out until retirement.

12:13.640 --> 12:14.766
I mean,

12:14.820 --> 12:16.424
if you're not firing me.

12:19.340 --> 12:21.729
- Rohan.

12:21.780 --> 12:23.293
- Pappa.

12:23.350 --> 12:24.647
- You came all the way
down here

12:24.700 --> 12:26.770
and won't say nothing to
your father?

12:26.830 --> 12:28.434
- I didn't wanna bother you.

12:28.480 --> 12:30.823
- Bother?
No, no.

12:30.880 --> 12:34.259
I wanna apologize to you, beta.

12:34.310 --> 12:36.266
- For what?

12:36.320 --> 12:39.130
- I know I've hurt
your feelings before,

12:39.190 --> 12:42.535
when I refused to support
your music.

12:42.580 --> 12:44.536
I should have been
more supportive of you.

12:46.940 --> 12:51.104
That doesn't mean that you use
Ella to get back at me.

12:51.160 --> 12:52.457
- What?

12:52.510 --> 12:53.807
- Yeah, she doesn't need to be
dragged into

12:53.860 --> 12:55.157
our family business.

12:55.200 --> 12:56.462
- Is that what you think
is going on?

12:56.510 --> 12:57.499
That I'm using her?

12:57.550 --> 12:59.506
- I am trying to protect her.

12:59.560 --> 13:01.289
- Excuse me.

13:01.340 --> 13:03.467
I'm hanging out with Ella
because I actually like her,

13:03.520 --> 13:05.249
not that it's any of
your business.

13:05.300 --> 13:06.688
- I think you are
misunderstanding me.

13:06.740 --> 13:08.696
- No, I'm understanding you
just fine.

13:08.740 --> 13:13.348
And I know it's hard for you
to comprehend, Pappa,

13:13.400 --> 13:15.868
but the reason I could stay
sober for a year

13:15.920 --> 13:19.481
was that I didn't have to deal
with this.

13:19.530 --> 13:21.839
I...

13:21.880 --> 13:23.484
I didn't have to deal with you.

13:36.250 --> 13:39.629
- Jessica, you should move back
to Sheepshead Bay.

13:39.680 --> 13:42.638
- Mom, I'd love to,
but my job is here.

13:42.690 --> 13:44.942
You know, most parents would be
proud their kid's a doctor.

13:44.990 --> 13:48.517
- Well, there's something
to be said about tradition.

13:48.560 --> 13:50.551
Our family has a tradition...

13:50.610 --> 13:53.511
- Of diabetes, heart disease,
and lung cancer.

13:54.740 --> 13:56.696
- People gotta die of
something.

13:56.740 --> 13:59.914
- Allison Medrano,
I need you to get back inside.

13:59.960 --> 14:01.359
- Who the hell are you?

14:01.400 --> 14:03.652
- Your doctor.
- Since when?

14:03.710 --> 14:07.532
- Well, since you had to be
evaluated for heart disease.

14:07.580 --> 14:08.888
Dr. Medrano.
- Dr. Reynolds,

14:08.930 --> 14:10.750
thank you for
taking care of my mom.

14:10.800 --> 14:12.529
- I don't need
taking care of.

14:12.590 --> 14:13.932
- We're gonna do a full
work-up,

14:13.980 --> 14:16.414
but I need you to get back
inside ﬁrst, all right?

14:16.460 --> 14:18.769
- Yeah, yeah.

14:18.810 --> 14:19.890
- Mom.
- Jeez--

14:22.940 --> 14:23.895
- Mom!

14:23.950 --> 14:25.554
- Hold on. Hold on.

14:25.600 --> 14:26.817
I need a stretcher out here!

14:26.860 --> 14:28.248
Okay.

14:36.440 --> 14:39.568
You get what's ironic
about this.

14:39.610 --> 14:41.874
- No.
Help me out.

14:41.920 --> 14:44.650
- I have a prescription
for Adderall.

14:44.700 --> 14:45.962
I mean, the risk would be

14:46.010 --> 14:48.615
